  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. **Money laundering** is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through complex transactions or businesses to make it appear legitimate. It is a criminal offense because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and organized crime, while concealing the source of the funds.\n\nLaws against money laundering are designed to disrupt criminal enterprises, prevent the financing of illegal activities, and maintain the integrity of financial systems. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment, depending on the severity of the crime and the jurisdiction.\n\nMany countries have established **anti-money laundering (AML)** regulations and agencies to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities. Financial institutions and businesses are often required to implement measures to identify and report suspicious transactions as part of these efforts.",
